7 Super Useful Aliases to make your development life easier üë®‚Äçüíª üë©‚Äçüíª

Let‚Äôs talk to your machine in your own language

Nowshad
3 min read
¬∑
Mar 9, 2018

npm install --save expresssudo apt-get updatebrew cask install docker

Commands like these are our daily routine. Software Developer, Dev ops, Data Scientists, System Admin or in any other profession, we need to play with a few regular commands again and again.

It‚Äôs tiresome to write these commands every time we need them üò´

Wouldn‚Äôt it be better if we could use some kind of shortcuts for these commands?

Meet Your Friend ‚Äî Alias

What if I tell you that you can use

nis express

Instead of

npm install --save express

Stay with me, we‚Äôll find out how üòâ

What‚Äôs alias ?

It‚Äôs a text-only interface for your terminal or shell commands that can be mapped with longer and more complex commands under the hood!

How ?

Open your terminal and type alias then press Enter

You‚Äôll see a list of available aliases on your machine.

Get Nowshad‚Äôs stories in your inbox

Join Medium for free to get updates from this writer.

If you look closely you‚Äôll find a common pattern to use aliases -

alias alias_name="command_to_run"

So, we‚Äôre simply mapping commands with names! (almost)

Let‚Äôs Create a few

NOTE: For the purpose of this tutorial, please keep your terminal open and use one terminal to test these aliases. use cd if you need to change directory.

1. Install node Packages

npm install --save packagename ‚û°Ô∏è nis packagename
Type the command below in your terminal and press Enter -

alias nis="npm install --save "

Now, we can use nis express to install express inside your node project.

2. Git add and commit

git add . && git commit -a -m "your commit message"
‚û°Ô∏è gac "your commit message"

alias gac="git add . && git commit -a -m "

WARNING: This is not a recommended alias to use, use it if and only if you know what you‚Äôe

3. Search Through Terminal History

history | grep keyword ‚û°Ô∏è hs keyword

alias hs='history | grep'

Now, if we need to search thorough our history to find everything with the keyword test we just have to execute hs test to find our expected result.

4. Make and enter inside a directory

mkdir -p test && cd test ‚û°Ô∏è mkcd test

alias mkcd='foo(){ mkdir -p "$1"; cd "$1" }; foo '

5. Show my ip address

curl http://ipecho.net/plain ‚û°Ô∏è myip

alias myip="curl http://ipecho.net/plain; echo"

6. Open file with admin access

sudo vim filename ‚û°Ô∏è svim filename

alias svim='sudo vim'

7. Update your linux pc/server

sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get update ‚û°Ô∏è update

alias update='sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade'

Persistant Aliases

You‚Äôve learnt how to create aliases. Now it‚Äôs time to make them persistent throughout your system. Depending on what type of shell/terminal you‚Äôre using you need to copy-paste your aliases inside ~/.bashrc or ~/.bashprofile or ~/.zshrc if you‚Äôre using zsh as your default terminal.

Example:

As I‚Äôm using zsh as my default terminal, I‚Äôve to edit ~/.zshrc file to add my aliases. First of all let‚Äôs open it with admin access with sudo vim ~/.zshrc .

Now, I need to paste my alias/aliases like alias hs='history | grep' then exit with saving by entering :wq inside vim

Then to take effect I need to execute source ~/.zshrc and restart my terminal. From now on, the hs command will be available throughout my system üòÉ

Bonus

oh-my-zsh is a great enhancement for your terminal which comes with some default aliases and beautiful interface.

As you‚Äôve learnt how to use aliases, let‚Äôs go and create some awesome aliases and share it in the response section.
